1
00:00:51,284 --> 00:00:53,445
[Man Narrating]
This is the Earth at a time...

2
00:00:53,520 --> 00:00:58,389
when the dinosaurs roamed
a lush and fertile planet.

3
00:01:05,732 --> 00:01:09,259
A piece of rock
just six miles wide...

4
00:01:09,335 --> 00:01:11,269
changed all that.

5
00:01:19,079 --> 00:01:23,015
It hit with the force
of 10,000 nuclear weapons.

6
00:01:26,119 --> 00:01:30,613
A trillion tons of dirt and rock
hurtled into the atmosphere,

7
00:01:30,690 --> 00:01:33,591
creating a suffocating
blanket of dust...

8
00:01:33,660 --> 00:01:36,185
the sun was powerless
to penetrate...

9
00:01:36,262 --> 00:01:38,696
for a thousand years.

10
00:01:46,806 --> 00:01:48,740
It happened before.

11
00:01:49,943 --> 00:01:52,275
It will happen again.

12
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:56,114
It's just a question of when.

13
00:02:11,931 --> 00:02:13,728
[Man Chattering]

14
00:02:17,170 --> 00:02:19,104
[Man] Houston, affirmative.

15
00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:22,374
Now try again.

16
00:02:22,442 --> 00:02:25,934
[Man On Radio Chattering]

17
00:02:26,012 --> 00:02:28,537
Almost got it.
[Grunts]

18
00:02:30,650 --> 00:02:34,552
- Dennis, I'm almost there.
- Houston, Pete's lookin' real strong.

19
00:02:34,621 --> 00:02:37,954
Okay, Pete, we got that coupling
on the board here now.

20
00:02:38,024 --> 00:02:41,391
We'll give you the go-ahead
from down here when it's in alignment.

21
00:02:41,461 --> 00:02:44,328
Sounds good.
Give me ten seconds.

22
00:02:44,397 --> 00:02:46,490
[Sighs]

23
00:02:46,566 --> 00:02:49,000
His heart rate's racing.
Hey, Pete.

24
00:02:49,068 --> 00:02:51,059
- It's Truman.
- Hey.

25
00:02:51,137 --> 00:02:53,571
- How you doing up there, hoss?
- Pretty good.

26
00:02:53,640 --> 00:02:56,666
Listen, Pete, we got an eye on your meds
here. I'll give you a buffalo nickel...

27
00:02:56,743 --> 00:02:58,404
if you'll calm down
just a little bit.

28
00:02:58,478 --> 00:03:01,345
- Can you do that for me?
- Whatever you say.

29
00:03:01,414 --> 00:03:04,906
Okay, now, we got plenty of time,
buddy, so don't you worry.

30
00:03:08,521 --> 00:03:10,716
Looking good here.

31
00:03:10,790 --> 00:03:12,553
He'll be all right.

32
00:03:12,625 --> 00:03:15,059
- Go ahead, Atlantis.
- Roger that, Houston.

33
00:03:15,128 --> 00:03:17,528
Suggest we start
reeling Pete in.

34
00:03:27,473 --> 00:03:30,135
- [Buzzing]
- What the hell is that?

35
00:03:30,210 --> 00:03:31,541
My Lord.

36
00:03:34,380 --> 00:03:36,314
[Screaming]

37
00:03:36,382 --> 00:03:38,373
We're down!

38
00:03:41,821 --> 00:03:43,618
Houston!

39
00:03:46,025 --> 00:03:48,550
We've lost all contact.

40
00:03:50,630 --> 00:03:53,326
Stewart, play that tape back!

41
00:03:56,502 --> 00:03:59,300
[Screaming] Houston!

42
00:04:01,307 --> 00:04:03,969
Multiple bogies! Multiple bogies!

43
00:04:04,043 --> 00:04:06,944
Sector five, niner.
I have three. Now five.

44
00:04:07,013 --> 00:04:09,174
- Unidentified tracks.
- My screen's full.

45
00:04:09,249 --> 00:04:11,080
Multiple tracks headed toward
the Atlantic seaboard!

46
00:04:11,150 --> 00:04:12,845
This could be a surprise missile attack.

47
00:04:12,919 --> 00:04:15,979
[Alarm Blaring]

48
00:04:18,591 --> 00:04:21,822
Mr. President, the shuttle
Atlantis just exploded in space.

49
00:04:21,894 --> 00:04:26,263
Okay, I want three groups!
One: Internal malfunction.

50
00:04:26,332 --> 00:04:28,926
Get the log tape.
Start working back. Maybe it's a glitch.

51
00:04:29,002 --> 00:04:32,335
Two: I want NORAD,
Space Command and the 50th tactical,

52
00:04:32,405 --> 00:04:34,600
comparing all the space junk
you tracked in every orbit.

53
00:04:34,674 --> 00:04:36,665
I want you to check, recheck
and then do it all over again.

54
00:04:36,743 --> 00:04:39,803
Number three: Wild cards.
Anything and everything.

55
00:04:39,879 --> 00:04:43,110
All right? Now, Big Ross, get on
the telephone. Wake up 11,000 people.

56
00:04:43,182 --> 00:04:45,116
- Walt, get 'em going.
- Let's go!

57
00:04:45,184 --> 00:04:50,053
Karl. Karl! Karl.

58
00:04:51,858 --> 00:04:54,986
Karl! Your Stouffer's pot pie's...

59
00:04:55,061 --> 00:04:57,359
been on the table almost ten hours.

60
00:04:57,430 --> 00:05:00,024
- I want a divorce.
- Dottie, I'm on to something big here.

61
00:05:00,099 --> 00:05:03,330
I- I don't know what this is, but it
looks like something's burnin' up there.

62
00:05:03,403 --> 00:05:07,362
Go get my phone book, will you? Get my phone
book. Get those names of those guys from NASA.

63
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:12,241
Excuse me! Am I wearing a sign
that says, "Karl's Slave"?

64
00:05:12,312 --> 00:05:15,372
Go get my goddamn phone book!

65
00:05:15,448 --> 00:05:19,009
Get the book!
Get the book! Get the book!

66
00:05:23,556 --> 00:05:27,424
Space Command is reporting negative.
That is zero global launches.

67
00:05:27,493 --> 00:05:29,723
It might just be a piece of the shuttle
breaking up as it comes in.

68
00:05:29,796 --> 00:05:33,698
It might be Santa Claus. Until we get
definitive, reliable confirmation, General,

69
00:05:33,766 --> 00:05:36,360
we go to DEFCON Three.

70
00:05:41,407 --> 00:05:44,934
¤ I'm gettin' ready
for the big time ¤

71
00:05:45,011 --> 00:05:49,505
¤ Someday you're gonna say
I'm big time too ¤

72
00:05:49,582 --> 00:05:51,516
Hey, little man!
Little Richard!

73
00:05:51,584 --> 00:05:54,348
Me and you, man!
We're going to the top, baby!

74
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:58,652
Big time! I ain't gonna be ridin'
this bike for the rest of my life.

75
00:05:58,725 --> 00:06:00,955
You know what I'm sayin'?
I'm gettin' a motorcycle, baby.

76
00:06:01,027 --> 00:06:04,292
We're gonna travel in style.

77
00:06:04,364 --> 00:06:08,300
¤ I'm gettin' ready for the big time ¤

78
00:06:08,368 --> 00:06:10,962
¤ Someday I'm gonna be
in big time news ¤

79
00:06:11,037 --> 00:06:14,803
Watch where you're goin'. I bet you,
none of you all stop for brothers.

80
00:06:14,874 --> 00:06:19,208
Slow down, Little Richard. You've been
ridin' all morning. You gotta take a dump?

81
00:06:20,913 --> 00:06:24,183
- We interrupt our regularly scheduled program...
- What happened?

82
00:06:24,316 --> 00:06:25,840
- To bring you this special report.
- Shh, shh, shh.

83
00:06:25,918 --> 00:06:31,254
The shuttle Atlantis exploded in space
at 3:47 a.m., Eastern Standard Time.

84
00:06:31,323 --> 00:06:33,553
- [Growling]
- [Squeaking]

85
00:06:33,625 --> 00:06:36,423
Hey! Get, get.

86
00:06:36,495 --> 00:06:39,328
[Chattering]

87
00:06:39,398 --> 00:06:42,333
- That's my Godzilla. Come on, now.
- Yo, fool!

88
00:06:42,401 --> 00:06:44,596
Don't be kickin' Little Richard.
What the hell your problem?

89
00:06:44,670 --> 00:06:47,605
That dog's eatin' my Godzilla. What's a
little runt like you gonna do about it?

90
00:06:47,673 --> 00:06:50,107
Get him, Richard. Sic him.
If I wasn't no Christian,

91
00:06:50,175 --> 00:06:54,111
I'd be throwin' your fat
pineapple-eatin' ass through the window.

92
00:06:58,150 --> 00:07:01,085
[Screaming]

93
00:07:06,692 --> 00:07:09,593
- Why we not going?
- You know why? 'Cause this is New York City.

94
00:07:09,661 --> 00:07:12,994
Anything could happen. Let's see.
Could've been a terrorist bomb.

95
00:07:13,065 --> 00:07:15,932
Could've been a dead body. Somebody
shot, stabbed, and it's Friday, payday.

96
00:07:16,001 --> 00:07:20,028
- Dude, somebody probably didn't get their paycheck. Yes?
- I want to go shopping.

97
00:07:20,105 --> 00:07:24,633
Me, too, but we ain't goin' nowhere
'cause this is a traffic jam.

98
00:07:24,710 --> 00:07:26,837
- Little Richard!
- Right over there!

99
00:07:26,912 --> 00:07:29,938
- [Screaming]
- Little Richard!

100
00:07:30,015 --> 00:07:31,983
Hang on, Little Richard.
I'm comin'!

101
00:07:32,050 --> 00:07:36,146
- [Whimpering]
- Don't you worry about it. I'm gonna get you outta there!

102
00:07:36,221 --> 00:07:39,554
You okay, buddy?
Don't worry about it. Hang in there.

103
00:07:39,625 --> 00:07:42,651
Somebody dial 911!

104
00:07:42,728 --> 00:07:44,696
My screen's full.
They're all over the place.

105
00:07:44,763 --> 00:07:48,324
Bogies are breachin' the atmosphere from
Finland down the North American seaboard.

106
00:07:51,937 --> 00:07:55,464
[Screaming]

107
00:07:58,744 --> 00:08:00,871
Whoa!

108
00:08:03,982 --> 00:08:06,507
Look at that!

109
00:08:11,990 --> 00:08:15,687
- Oh, we at war!
- [Screaming Continues]

110
00:08:15,761 --> 00:08:17,729
Saddam Hussein is bombing us!

111
00:08:46,191 --> 00:08:48,682
[Man Screaming]

112
00:09:12,984 --> 00:09:16,044
- Let's stay focused. We need to map the trajectory now.
- That could take a week.

113
00:09:16,121 --> 00:09:18,646
Just find it, okay? I wanna know if
the worst is over or if it's on its way.

114
00:09:18,724 --> 00:09:20,453
We've got General Kimsey on the line.

115
00:09:20,525 --> 00:09:23,153
We've got hits from Finland
to South Carolina.

116
00:09:23,228 --> 00:09:25,162
We know they're not missiles.
Now what the hell is it?

117
00:09:25,230 --> 00:09:28,666
It's a meteor shower.
That's what took out the shuttle.

118
00:09:28,734 --> 00:09:31,464
[Overlapping Chattering]

119
00:09:31,536 --> 00:09:34,096
I've got the president
on Air Force One demanding answers.

120
00:09:34,172 --> 00:09:36,606
[General]
Is it over?

121
00:09:36,675 --> 00:09:39,803
General, we've got 11,000 people at NASA
trying to figure that out right now.

122
00:09:39,878 --> 00:09:41,311
When we know, you'll know.

123
00:09:44,216 --> 00:09:46,411
[Sirens Wailing]

124
00:09:46,551 --> 00:09:50,487
Okay, Karl, listen. I want you to take your
time. Yes, sir. You're definitely the first.

125
00:09:50,555 --> 00:09:55,686
Okay, first coordinate.
One-two-three-nine. 1239, right?

126
00:09:55,761 --> 00:09:59,356
- F.B.I. Locked his location.
- Saw an explosion in space.

127
00:09:59,431 --> 00:10:02,662
- Okay.
- [Whispering]

128
00:10:02,734 --> 00:10:05,259
- Listen, Karl, this is top secret.
- Sir, I'm retired Navy.

129
00:10:05,337 --> 00:10:07,862
I know all about classified.
But one more thing.

130
00:10:07,939 --> 00:10:10,339
The person that finds her
gets to name her, right?

131
00:10:10,409 --> 00:10:14,675
- Yes, that's right.
- I wanna name her Dottie, after my wife.

132
00:10:14,746 --> 00:10:18,773
She's a vicious life-suckin' bitch
from which there's no escape.

133
00:10:18,850 --> 00:10:21,512
- That's sweet, Karl.
- S.D.I., this is flight director!

134
00:10:21,586 --> 00:10:24,350
- I wanna get that Hubble movin', and I want it now.
- Roger that.

135
00:10:24,423 --> 00:10:26,288
We're movin' the Hubble!

136
00:10:32,964 --> 00:10:34,192
[Man]
It's enormous.

137
00:10:34,266 --> 00:10:38,293
This is the anomaly at 1643.

138
00:10:39,571 --> 00:10:43,803
Here is the anomaly at 1658,

139
00:10:43,875 --> 00:10:47,367
and here is the anomaly at 1700.

140
00:10:47,446 --> 00:10:49,971
Enough with this anomaly horseshit!

141
00:10:50,048 --> 00:10:53,484
- What is this thing?
- It's an asteroid, sir.

142
00:10:53,552 --> 00:10:56,419
How big are we talking?

143
00:10:56,488 --> 00:10:58,979
Sir, our best estimate is 97.6 billion...

144
00:10:59,057 --> 00:11:01,992
- It's the size of Texas, Mr. President.
- Y-Yes, sir.

145
00:11:02,060 --> 00:11:03,857
Dan, we didn't see this thing coming?

146
00:11:03,929 --> 00:11:06,193
Well, our object collision
budget's a million dollars.

147
00:11:06,264 --> 00:11:08,494
That allows us to track
about three percent of the sky.

148
00:11:08,567 --> 00:11:10,899
And begging your pardon, sir,
it's a big-ass sky.

149
00:11:10,969 --> 00:11:14,496
- And the ones this morning?
- Those are nothing. They're the size of basketballs...

150
00:11:14,573 --> 00:11:16,541
and Volkswagens,
things like that.

151
00:11:16,608 --> 00:11:21,204
- Is this going to hit us?
- We're efforting that as we speak, sir.

152
00:11:21,279 --> 00:11:23,907
- What kind of damage are we...
- Damage?

153
00:11:25,217 --> 00:11:27,242
Total, sir.

154
00:11:27,319 --> 00:11:29,787
It's what we call a global killer.

155
00:11:29,855 --> 00:11:32,016
The end of mankind.

156
00:11:32,090 --> 00:11:34,285
Doesn't matter where it hits.

157
00:11:34,359 --> 00:11:36,589
Nothing would survive.
Not even bacteria.

158
00:11:36,661 --> 00:11:40,791
My God. What do we do?

159
00:11:40,866 --> 00:11:42,800
[Groaning]

160
00:11:49,708 --> 00:11:52,973
We have 18 days before it hits Earth.

161
00:12:02,387 --> 00:12:06,221
- [Man] Have mercy.
- Rise and shine!

162
00:12:06,291 --> 00:12:08,259
[Yelling]

163
00:12:08,326 --> 00:12:11,386
Stop the drilling!
Stop the drilling! Stop the drilling!

164
00:12:11,463 --> 00:12:14,091
Fore!

165
00:12:14,165 --> 00:12:16,065
Stop the drilling! Stop the drilling!

166
00:12:16,134 --> 00:12:19,103
- Hey!
- Hey, that was close!

167
00:12:19,170 --> 00:12:22,003
[Chuckling]

168
00:12:22,073 --> 00:12:25,839
I give you 50,000 a year in donations.

169
00:12:25,911 --> 00:12:28,345
- What do you think they're so mad about, Chick?
- Well, I think they feel...

170
00:12:28,413 --> 00:12:30,677
that drilling for oil
is an evil thing.

171
00:12:30,749 --> 00:12:33,411
You know how much diesel
that clunker boat pumps out an hour?

172
00:12:33,485 --> 00:12:38,752
I just found out something interesting.
Number two chewed 180 feet last night.

173
00:12:38,823 --> 00:12:41,314
- Who do we have to thank for this?
- I'll give you two guesses.

174
00:12:41,393 --> 00:12:43,861
But you're only gonna need one.

175
00:12:43,929 --> 00:12:45,328
Goddamn it, A.J.!

176
00:12:45,397 --> 00:12:47,490
A.J.!

177
00:12:49,334 --> 00:12:52,997
A.J.! A.J., you in here?

178
00:12:53,071 --> 00:12:55,631
Oh, that's just perfect.
In bed. Get up!

179
00:12:55,707 --> 00:12:59,768
- Uh, hey, you wanted to see me?
- Yeah, I was lookin' for ya.

180
00:12:59,844 --> 00:13:01,778
You're pissed. Okay, I can see that.

181
00:13:01,846 --> 00:13:04,815
No. You know what, A.J.?
I'm not pissed. You've seen me pissed.

182
00:13:04,883 --> 00:13:08,717
This is way, way beyond pissed, though. You
know I shut down number two last night, right?

183
00:13:08,787 --> 00:13:11,187
- Yeah, man, I had a hunch on that.
- Let me tell you something.

184
00:13:11,256 --> 00:13:14,191
Someday, many years from now,
when you're all growed up,

185
00:13:14,259 --> 00:13:18,696
and you got your own oil company and $8
million of your own money on the contract,

186
00:13:18,763 --> 00:13:22,358
you can do whatever comes into that little
A.J. -idiotin' mind of yours you want.

187
00:13:22,434 --> 00:13:25,835
But as long as it says "Harry Stamper Oil"
on the rig, you will not disobey my rules.

188
00:13:25,904 --> 00:13:27,838
- You got that?
- Yeah, I do got it.

189
00:13:27,906 --> 00:13:30,397
All right, now I need to hear
five words from you.

190
00:13:30,475 --> 00:13:32,636
- Uh...
- I'll...

191
00:13:32,711 --> 00:13:34,804
[Together]
Never do that again.

192
00:13:34,879 --> 00:13:37,347
I'm a fool. That was idiotic.
I- I mean, that was stupid.

193
00:13:37,415 --> 00:13:39,076
I'm an idiot. I know
what name's on the sign. I'm not...

194
00:13:39,150 --> 00:13:40,981
- What's goin' on here?
- What's goin' on?

195
00:13:41,052 --> 00:13:42,917
Well, I-I mean, you know,
I screwed up. I'm a little edgy.

196
00:13:42,988 --> 00:13:46,151
- How long you work for me?
- Five wonderful years.

197
00:13:46,224 --> 00:13:49,819
In five years, you have never
apologized to me this quickly.

198
00:13:49,894 --> 00:13:51,885
- Something's going on here. I'm gonna find out what it is.
- [Stammering]

199
00:13:51,963 --> 00:13:55,490
Well, I'm turning over a new leaf.
I'm trying to learn from the man.

200
00:13:55,567 --> 00:13:57,660
What would Harry do?

201
00:14:02,974 --> 00:14:06,273
I'm at a loss for words.

202
00:14:06,344 --> 00:14:07,868
Okay, I can explain this.

203
00:14:07,946 --> 00:14:09,573
- You can explain that?
- I can.

204
00:14:09,648 --> 00:14:13,317
I would really like an explanation.
You just stay right here.

205
00:14:18,655 --> 00:14:20,850
Grace?

206
00:14:20,924 --> 00:14:25,293
- Hi, Harry.
- I have asked you repeatedly to call me Dad.

207
00:14:25,362 --> 00:14:27,387
Sorry, Harry.

208
00:14:27,464 --> 00:14:30,058
Get up and get your clothes on.

209
00:14:31,802 --> 00:14:35,363
You just stay right there.
I'll be right back.

210
00:14:42,479 --> 00:14:46,415
Here's what we're gonna do. I want every
strategy we've got on near-Earth object collision.

211
00:14:46,483 --> 00:14:52,012
Okay? Any ideas, any programs, anything you
sketched on a pizza box or cocktail napkin.

212
00:14:52,089 --> 00:14:55,286
For 30 years, they questioned the need for
NASA. Today, we're gonna give 'em the answer.

213
00:14:58,862 --> 00:15:01,126
You know about this, Rockhound?

214
00:15:01,198 --> 00:15:04,065
- You knew?
- No, I had no idea.

215
00:15:05,569 --> 00:15:08,265
Where's Harry?

216
00:15:08,338 --> 00:15:11,102
Harry, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.
I understand, okay?

217
00:15:11,174 --> 00:15:13,665
You're mad.
Who-Who wouldn't be mad?

218
00:15:13,744 --> 00:15:15,769
- He's gonna shoot you.
- Nah, no, he's not.

219
00:15:15,846 --> 00:15:19,976
Oh, shit.
[Screaming]

220
00:15:20,050 --> 00:15:23,019
- Harry!
- What's wrong with you?

221
00:15:23,086 --> 00:15:25,247
Make your peace with God, A.J.!

222
00:15:25,322 --> 00:15:27,415
This guy's got a gun, man.
He's shooting at me.

223
00:15:27,491 --> 00:15:31,655
- Harry, this is not funny!
- Harry, listen to me! We can talk this over!

224
00:15:31,728 --> 00:15:34,788
- Oh, is this a serious thing?
- Yeah, pretty serious.

225
00:15:34,865 --> 00:15:36,389
- Bear!
- What's up?

226
00:15:36,466 --> 00:15:38,866
He's shootin' at me. You see Harry
comin', crack him with that wrench.

227
00:15:38,935 --> 00:15:42,166
You told A.J.'s dad just before he died
that you would take care of the boy.

228
00:15:42,239 --> 00:15:44,332
Now I'm not sure that
shootin' him is takin' care of him.

229
00:15:44,408 --> 00:15:47,673
- Why don't you put the gun down?
- You don't want none of this. Get out of my way.

230
00:15:47,744 --> 00:15:49,939
Just tryin' to give my man
a head start, that's all.

231
00:15:50,013 --> 00:15:52,948
Not to mention the fact that I don't think
you wanna kill the best man on your crew...

232
00:15:53,016 --> 00:15:55,109
- before we strike oil.
- Aw, Chick, I ain't gonna kill him.

233
00:15:55,185 --> 00:15:58,279
Just gonna take a foot off.
A man can work with one foot.

234
00:15:58,355 --> 00:16:01,051
You remember old Frank Marx who worked
with one hand all them years?

235
00:16:01,124 --> 00:16:02,557
Yeah, but he wasn't very good.

236
00:16:02,626 --> 00:16:05,527
Harry, put the gun down!
You're acting insane!

237
00:16:05,595 --> 00:16:08,029
Now, honey, go get some clothes on
and get out of the way.

238
00:16:08,098 --> 00:16:12,626
- You can't control my life!
- Fine. Clothes. Now!

239
00:16:12,702 --> 00:16:15,637
All right, stop! All right! It was funny
for a minute. It's not funny anymore.

240
00:16:17,441 --> 00:16:20,467
- Fuck!
- Harry, this is illegal, man.

241
00:16:20,544 --> 00:16:22,808
I'm temporarily insane, Rock.
It's all right.

242
00:16:22,879 --> 00:16:25,871
[Screaming]

243
00:16:27,751 --> 00:16:29,582
- Do I look like I'm crazy to you?
- Well...

244
00:16:29,653 --> 00:16:31,177
Harry! Harry! Harry!

245
00:16:31,254 --> 00:16:36,419
All right, now, listen.
Man to man. I'm serious. I love her.

246
00:16:36,493 --> 00:16:38,393
Way wrong answer!

247
00:16:38,462 --> 00:16:41,158
[Screaming]

248
00:16:41,231 --> 00:16:44,029
- Whoa, whoa, Harry. It's gettin' real.
- Harry! Come on, Harry!

249
00:16:44,100 --> 00:16:46,830
- You shot me!
- You shot him.

250
00:16:46,903 --> 00:16:48,837
That bullet never got close.
Just a ricochet.

251
00:16:48,905 --> 00:16:51,271
You know, it's all funny
till somebody gets shot in the leg!

252
00:16:51,341 --> 00:16:55,277
Hey, pucker up.
We got clients incoming.

253
00:16:56,646 --> 00:16:59,706
Uh, b-back in-in... in 1974,

254
00:16:59,783 --> 00:17:03,275
we-we first got the idea... the-the
possibility that-that a meteor or an asteroid...

255
00:17:03,353 --> 00:17:05,913
I need somebody who's had a little less
caffeine this morning. Doc, translate.

256
00:17:05,989 --> 00:17:11,052
Yes, sir. Our first feasibility plan was
to use a spread-focus laser generator...

257
00:17:11,127 --> 00:17:13,095
to heat the object
to the point of fracture.

258
00:17:13,163 --> 00:17:15,461
That's like shooting a B.B. Gun
at a freight train, Doc.

259
00:17:15,532 --> 00:17:17,466
Uh, some of us have got this idea.

260
00:17:17,534 --> 00:17:21,095
We wanna land a craft,
deploy solar sails.

261
00:17:21,171 --> 00:17:26,768
You'll have a big canopy. Solar winds
will be caught by these Mylar sails.

262
00:17:26,843 --> 00:17:29,641
- Okay...
- Come on, guys!

263
00:17:29,713 --> 00:17:33,479
We gotta come up with something
realistic here. We got 18 days.

264
00:17:33,550 --> 00:17:37,281
That's 431 hours, 15 minutes
and 18 seconds.

265
00:17:37,354 --> 00:17:41,085
Time's a luxury we don't have. What?

266
00:17:42,626 --> 00:17:44,992
Listen, Harry, A.J. Is my choice.

267
00:17:45,061 --> 00:17:48,553
- My choice and not yours.
- He's the only one in your age bracket, Grace.

268
00:17:48,632 --> 00:17:50,566
It's not a choice.
It's a lack of options.

269
00:17:50,634 --> 00:17:53,034
I don't know
what in the world makes you think...

270
00:17:53,103 --> 00:17:55,833
that you have the right
to tell me what to do anymore, Harry.

271
00:17:55,906 --> 00:17:57,840
I suppose being your father
doesn't count, huh?

272
00:17:57,908 --> 00:17:59,500
- Not really.
- Since when?

273
00:17:59,576 --> 00:18:03,103
Since I reached the age of ten
and became older than you, Harry.

274
00:18:03,179 --> 00:18:05,113
Since Mom split.
Why don't you take your pick?

275
00:18:05,181 --> 00:18:10,619
Look, I understand that you are handicapped
by natural immaturity, and I forgive you.

276
00:18:10,687 --> 00:18:13,884
I may be an immature father,
but I'm still your employer.

277
00:18:13,957 --> 00:18:17,154
And as your boss, I want you on that crew
boat tonight and back in the office by Monday.

278
00:18:17,227 --> 00:18:20,355
- You got that?
- Okay. I quit.

279
00:18:20,430 --> 00:18:23,263
Grace, you can't quit now!

280
00:18:23,333 --> 00:18:25,665
- I need you to keep on working.
- [Speaking Chinese Dialect]

281
00:18:26,870 --> 00:18:29,532
Hi, Harry!

282
00:18:29,606 --> 00:18:31,836
- What are you smilin' about?
- [Speaking Chinese Dialect]

283
00:18:31,908 --> 00:18:36,436
I've been seein' A.J.
For more than five months, Harry.

284
00:18:36,513 --> 00:18:38,447
[Speaking Chinese Dialect]

285
00:18:38,515 --> 00:18:41,040
You little hypocrite. I ever
held you back once from doing anything?

286
00:18:41,117 --> 00:18:43,051
What about having a life, Harry?

287
00:18:43,119 --> 00:18:47,021
The first time I got my period, Rockhound
had to take me into Taipei for Tampax...

288
00:18:47,090 --> 00:18:49,183
and then he had to show me
how to use 'em, Harry.

289
00:18:49,259 --> 00:18:51,193
Ho-ho.

290
00:18:51,261 --> 00:18:55,527
I ju... No, I-I told her how to
use it. I didn't show her, Harry.

291
00:18:55,599 --> 00:19:00,536
I was playing with titanium depth gauges
when I should've been playing with dolls.

292
00:19:00,604 --> 00:19:04,870
I mean, I learned about the birds and
the bees from Freddie Noonan's tattoos.

293
00:19:04,941 --> 00:19:07,671
Look, I was raised
on roughnecks by you.

294
00:19:07,744 --> 00:19:10,338
And now you get all shocked and shaken
when I fall in love with one.

295
00:19:10,413 --> 00:19:13,507
- So who's the hypocrite here, Harry, huh?
- Look at those nice pipes.

296
00:19:13,583 --> 00:19:17,383
- Listen to me, Grace.
- No, you listen to me, Harry. I grew up.

297
00:19:17,454 --> 00:19:21,652
With the proximity
of the asteroid and no prep time,

298
00:19:21,725 --> 00:19:23,989
none of our primary plans can work.

299
00:19:24,060 --> 00:19:27,552
Why don't we just send up 150 nuclear
warheads and blast that rock apart?

300
00:19:27,631 --> 00:19:29,428
Terrible idea.

301
00:19:29,499 --> 00:19:31,763
Was I talkin' to you?

302
00:19:31,835 --> 00:19:33,666
This is Dr. Ronald Quincy from Research.

303
00:19:33,737 --> 00:19:36,570
Pretty much the smartest man on the
planet. You might wanna listen to him.

304
00:19:36,640 --> 00:19:39,234
General, if you consider your target,

305
00:19:39,309 --> 00:19:41,743
her composition, her dimensions,

306
00:19:41,811 --> 00:19:43,745
her sheer velocity,

307
00:19:43,813 --> 00:19:48,807
you could fire every nuke you've got on her,
she'll just smile at you and keep on coming.

308
00:19:48,885 --> 00:19:50,876
You should know that
the president's scientific advisors...

309
00:19:50,954 --> 00:19:54,788
are suggesting that a nuclear blast
could change this asteroid's trajectory.

310
00:19:54,858 --> 00:19:59,557
I know the president's chief scientific
advisor. We were at M.I.T. Together.

311
00:19:59,629 --> 00:20:01,927
And, in a situation like this,
[Clears Throat]

312
00:20:01,998 --> 00:20:06,230
You really don't wanna take the advice from
a man who got a C-minus in astrophysics.

313
00:20:06,302 --> 00:20:11,535
The president's advisors
are wrong. I'm right.

314
00:20:11,608 --> 00:20:14,304
Hitting the rock from
the outside won't do the job.

315
00:20:14,377 --> 00:20:17,642
Imagine a firecracker
in the palm of your hand.

316
00:20:17,714 --> 00:20:21,206
You set it off. What happens?
Burn your hand, right?

317
00:20:21,284 --> 00:20:25,516
You close your fist around
the same firecracker and set it off...

318
00:20:25,588 --> 00:20:29,820
poof... your wife's gonna be opening your
ketchup bottles the rest of your life.

319
00:20:29,893 --> 00:20:32,418
Are you suggesting that we blow
this thing up from the inside?

320
00:20:32,495 --> 00:20:34,463
- That's exactly what I'm saying.
- How?

321
00:20:34,531 --> 00:20:37,022
[Sighs]
We drill.

322
00:20:37,100 --> 00:20:39,227
We bring in the world's best
deep-core driller.

323
00:20:39,302 --> 00:20:41,270
Harry, get up here.
We're takin' a hit.

324
00:20:41,337 --> 00:20:43,965
- Get A.J. Up here!
- Come on!

325
00:20:44,040 --> 00:20:45,905
- Oh, shit!
- [Yelling]

326
00:20:45,975 --> 00:20:48,239
Send another pipe down! Right now!

327
00:20:48,311 --> 00:20:51,303
- [Yelling Continues]
- It's a gas pocket!

328
00:20:51,381 --> 00:20:53,679
I told you! Am I lucky,
or am I just a genius?

329
00:20:53,750 --> 00:20:56,810
I shut it down for a reason,
you jackass! The relief valve's...

330
00:20:56,886 --> 00:20:59,684
[Screaming]

331
00:20:59,756 --> 00:21:04,159
Shut off the number two valve!
Grace, get the clients out of here now!

332
00:21:04,227 --> 00:21:06,491
[Alarm Blaring]

333
00:21:06,563 --> 00:21:09,828
- No, Daddy!
- [Screaming]

334
00:21:09,899 --> 00:21:13,096
Chick, get 'em outta here!
Get 'em off the rig now!

335
00:21:18,675 --> 00:21:21,200
- Get the hell down!
- This thing is gonna blow.

336
00:21:25,415 --> 00:21:27,542
[Screaming]

337
00:21:27,617 --> 00:21:31,678
- [Yelling Continues]
- Chick, get down now!

338
00:21:31,755 --> 00:21:35,953
Get down!

339
00:21:36,025 --> 00:21:39,051
[Dan] Three dozen research calls, and
every time, the same man is recommended.

340
00:21:39,129 --> 00:21:41,495
He's worked on every terrain
this planet can offer.

341
00:21:41,564 --> 00:21:44,397
Whenever they said it couldn't be
drilled, this guy drilled it.

342
00:21:44,467 --> 00:21:47,561
- Everybody all right?
- We struck oil, baby!

343
00:21:47,637 --> 00:21:51,164
Somebody could've got killed out here
today. You want that on your conscience?

344
00:21:53,777 --> 00:21:55,745
High thumb.
You are man, Harry.

345
00:21:55,812 --> 00:21:58,576
- Thumbs high.
- [Helicopter Blades Whirring]

346
00:22:00,216 --> 00:22:02,207
You're fired.

347
00:22:07,122 --> 00:22:09,682
Who's Harry Stamper?

348
00:22:09,758 --> 00:22:12,989
Hey, I'm Harry Stamper.
What's all this about?

349
00:22:13,062 --> 00:22:16,225
Mr. Stamper, I'm General Montgomery,
commander of the Pacific air forces.

350
00:22:16,298 --> 00:22:19,062
I've been sent here
by the secretary of defense...

351
00:22:19,134 --> 00:22:21,762
on direct orders
from the president of the United States.

352
00:22:21,837 --> 00:22:25,034
- [Chuckling]
- It's a matter of urgent national security.

353
00:22:25,107 --> 00:22:28,270
I need you to get on that chopper
right now, no questions asked.

354
00:22:28,344 --> 00:22:30,403
Crazy Willie put you up to this?

355
00:22:30,479 --> 00:22:34,916
I'm afraid I don't know Crazy Willie,
sir. I'm dead serious about this.

356
00:22:36,251 --> 00:22:38,719
- Harry.
- What?

357
00:22:38,787 --> 00:22:40,755
I swear to God,
she never told me her age.

358
00:22:40,823 --> 00:22:44,190
It's all right. Relax. It's about me.

359
00:22:44,259 --> 00:22:46,693
Oh. Forget it!

360
00:22:50,666 --> 00:22:54,966
All right, General,
I'll go with you on one condition.

361
00:22:55,037 --> 00:22:56,971
We're gonna have
to take my daughter along.

362
00:22:59,441 --> 00:23:01,875
- What did I do?
- Whoa, whoa, whoa. Where you guys takin' her?

363
00:23:01,944 --> 00:23:04,208
- Sir, stay right here.
- Wh...

364
00:23:04,279 --> 00:23:07,271
Chick, get him paid,
get him off the rig!

365
00:23:17,226 --> 00:23:20,662
- Mr. Stamper?
- Yeah, I'm Harry Stamper.

366
00:23:20,729 --> 00:23:23,095
How you doin'? Miss Stamper.

367
00:23:23,165 --> 00:23:25,099
I'm Dan Truman, Executive Director here.

368
00:23:25,167 --> 00:23:27,431
- Listen, on behalf of all of us, I'd really like to apologize...
- Apologize.

369
00:23:27,503 --> 00:23:29,869
I don't know if we can take
any more apologies, Mr. Truman.

370
00:23:29,938 --> 00:23:32,463
We've been apologized to
for the last 18-and-a-half hours.

371
00:23:32,541 --> 00:23:35,601
So if you don't mind, how about
if we just get on with it?

372
00:23:35,677 --> 00:23:37,577
You tell us why we're here
at the NASA Space Center.

373
00:23:37,646 --> 00:23:39,807
We should probably talk alone.

374
00:23:39,882 --> 00:23:42,476
Mr. Truman, I don't keep
any secrets from my daughter, Grace.

375
00:23:42,551 --> 00:23:45,987
So whether you tell her now or I tell her
later, she's gonna find out one way or the other.

376
00:23:46,054 --> 00:23:47,988
So why don't we just get on with it?

377
00:23:48,056 --> 00:23:51,992
[Dan] So when the Rogue comet hit the
asteroid belt, it sent shrapnel right for us.

378
00:23:52,060 --> 00:23:55,325
For the next 15 days,
the Earth's in a shooting gallery.

379
00:23:55,397 --> 00:23:59,299
Even if the asteroid itself
hits the water, it's still hitting land.

380
00:23:59,368 --> 00:24:04,169
It'll flash boil millions of gallons of
seawater and slam into the ocean bedrock.

381
00:24:04,239 --> 00:24:07,606
Now, if it's a Pacific Ocean impact...
which we think it will be...

382
00:24:07,676 --> 00:24:10,509
it'll create a tidal wave
three miles high,

383
00:24:10,579 --> 00:24:15,209
traveling at 1,000 miles an hour covering
California and washing up in Denver.

384
00:24:15,284 --> 00:24:18,879
Japan's gone.
Australia's wiped out.

385
00:24:18,954 --> 00:24:22,583
Half the world's population
will be incinerated by the heat blast.

386
00:24:22,658 --> 00:24:24,819
The rest'll freeze to death
from nuclear winter.

387
00:24:24,893 --> 00:24:27,657
[Whispering]
That's unbelievable.

388
00:24:27,729 --> 00:24:31,722
Well, actually,
this is as real as it gets.

389
00:24:34,169 --> 00:24:36,637
Well, it's coming right now.

390
00:24:36,705 --> 00:24:39,902
Right for us at 22,000 miles an hour.

391
00:24:39,975 --> 00:24:43,240
Not a soul on Earth can hide from it.

392
00:24:58,460 --> 00:25:01,190
I take it you're not
alerting everyone like this.

393
00:25:01,263 --> 00:25:04,061
Nobody knows.
That's the way it stays.

394
00:25:04,132 --> 00:25:07,533
For the next ten days, there are
only nine telescopes in the world...

395
00:25:07,603 --> 00:25:09,867
that can spot the asteroid,
and we control eight of 'em.

396
00:25:09,938 --> 00:25:12,930
The president's classified
this information top secret.

397
00:25:13,008 --> 00:25:14,908
If news like this got out,

398
00:25:14,977 --> 00:25:18,344
there'd be an overnight breakdown
of basic social services worldwide.

399
00:25:18,413 --> 00:25:23,749
Rioting, mass religious hysteria,
total chaos, you can imagine.

400
00:25:23,819 --> 00:25:26,947
Basically the worst parts of the Bible.

401
00:25:29,358 --> 00:25:32,725
Six billion people on the planet.

402
00:25:32,794 --> 00:25:35,092
Why'd you guys call me?

403
00:25:35,163 --> 00:25:38,599
- We need you to prep the team we're sending up.
- Up?

404
00:25:38,667 --> 00:25:42,194
We'll send them to the asteroid, they'll
land, drill a hole, they'll drop some nukes,

405
00:25:42,271 --> 00:25:45,263
take off and detonate,
if we can fix this equipment problem.

406
00:25:45,340 --> 00:25:50,243
The drilling unit's a prototype we've
been building for the Mars project.

407
00:25:50,312 --> 00:25:54,214
You, uh... You might recognize the rig.

408
00:25:54,283 --> 00:25:58,549
Yeah, well, I guess
I should recognize it. It's my design.

409
00:25:58,620 --> 00:26:01,214
- [Man Chattering On P.A.]
- [Helicopter Blades Whirring]

410
00:26:01,290 --> 00:26:04,953
- Did you steal a key to the Patent Office?
- Yeah, basically.

411
00:26:05,027 --> 00:26:07,894
Let me get this straight.
I got pulled off an oil rig,

412
00:26:07,963 --> 00:26:11,057
flown halfway around the world
because you stole my drill design.

413
00:26:11,133 --> 00:26:15,126
Couldn't read the plans right and did
a pisspoor job of putting it together.

414
00:26:15,203 --> 00:26:17,728
- Patents don't apply to outer space.
- [Dan] You shut up, Quincy.

415
00:26:17,806 --> 00:26:21,242
It's not going to Mars anymore.
It's gonna try to save this planet.

416
00:26:21,310 --> 00:26:23,574
And we need to know
what's wrong with it pretty quick.

417
00:26:23,645 --> 00:26:26,808
- You said we did a bad job of putting it together?
- No, I said...

418
00:26:26,882 --> 00:26:29,248
you did a pisspoor job
of putting it together.

419
00:26:29,318 --> 00:26:32,651
First of all, you got the flow system
all reversed. Let me guess.

420
00:26:32,721 --> 00:26:36,350
- You've been tearin' up rotors and you can't figure out why.
- Yeah, that's right.

421
00:26:36,425 --> 00:26:39,019
Well, that's because
your cams are all wrong, Mr. Wizard.

422
00:26:39,094 --> 00:26:42,359
Who's been operating this thing?

423
00:26:42,431 --> 00:26:44,797
- Right there.
- We've actually...

424
00:26:44,866 --> 00:26:48,461
- We've had them training for eight months solid now.
- Eight whole months?

425
00:26:48,537 --> 00:26:51,028
- Well, pretty much, yeah.
- Well, gee whiz.

426
00:26:51,106 --> 00:26:53,506
Well, this is the team
that has to do the job up there.

427
00:26:53,575 --> 00:26:55,600
We need you to train them down here.

428
00:26:55,677 --> 00:26:57,440
Well, Mr. Stamper, what do you think?

429
00:26:57,512 --> 00:27:00,709
You know, drilling's a science.
It's an art.

430
00:27:00,782 --> 00:27:02,977
I'm a third generation driller,
doin' it all my life.

431
00:27:03,051 --> 00:27:05,315
I still haven't got it all figured out.

432
00:27:05,387 --> 00:27:08,686
I assume you sent for me because
somebody told you I was the best.

433
00:27:08,757 --> 00:27:11,658
Well, I'm only the best
because I work with the best.

434
00:27:11,727 --> 00:27:15,663
You don't trust the men you're working
with, you're as good as dead.

435
00:27:15,731 --> 00:27:17,892
Now you wanna send
these boys into space, fine.

436
00:27:17,966 --> 00:27:19,900
I'm sure they'll make good astronauts,

437
00:27:19,968 --> 00:27:22,698
but they don't know jack about drillin'.

438
00:27:22,771 --> 00:27:25,535
- What's your contingency plan?
- Contingency plan?

439
00:27:25,607 --> 00:27:27,802
Your backup plan. You gotta have
some kind of backup plan, right?

440
00:27:27,876 --> 00:27:29,844
No, we don't have a backup plan.

441
00:27:29,911 --> 00:27:31,845
- This is it.
- This is the best that you could...

442
00:27:31,913 --> 00:27:35,314
that the government...
the U.S. Government can come up with.

443
00:27:35,384 --> 00:27:38,683
I mean, you're NASA for cryin' out loud.
You put a man on the moon.

444
00:27:38,754 --> 00:27:42,053
You're geniuses.
You're the guys that think this shit up.

445
00:27:42,124 --> 00:27:44,649
I'm sure you got a team of men
sittin' around somewhere right now,

446
